ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="The issue is that `vi.mock` is hoisted, so the mock variables defined
at the top level cannot be accessed inside the mock factories. I need to restruc
ture the CityPlugin test so that the mock factories don't reference top-level va
riables, or use `vi.doMock` instead, or define the mocks differently.\n\nA commo
n pattern is to use a `mockState` object that the mock factories return referenc
es to, and then mutate that object in `beforeEach`. But the hoisting issue is th
at the factory functions can't reference variables declared in the same scope.\n
\nActually, the simplest fix is to define the mock implementations directly insi
de the `vi.mock` factories without referencing external variables. But then I ne
ed a way to reset/inspect them.\n\nAnother approach: use `vi.doMock` (not hoiste
d) inside `beforeEach`, or use `vi.mock` with inline factory functions that use 
a global object.\n\nLet me try a different approach - define a global `__CITY_PL
UGIN_MOCKS__` object that the factories reference:\n\n```typescript\nconst __CIT
Y_PLUGIN_MOCKS__ = (global as any).__CITY_PLUGIN_MOCKS__ = {\n  cityMap: { ... }
,\n  uiManager: { ... },\n  // etc\n};\n\nvi.mock('../../scenes/main/city/Isomet
ricCityMap', () => ({\n  IsometricCityMap: vi.fn(() => (global as any).__CITY_PL
UGIN_MOCKS__.cityMap),\n}));\n```\n\nWait, but even referencing `global` inside 
the factory might work since it's a global. Let me try this approach.\n\nActuall
y, the cleanest approach is to use `vi.mock` with `importOriginal` and a factory
that doesn't reference outer scope variables. But for complex mocks, the standar
d pattern is:\n\n1. Put all mutable mock state on `vi.hoisted(() => ({ ... }))`\
n2. Reference that hoisted object in both the mock factories and the tests\n\nLe
t me rewrite the test using `vi.hoisted`.",
    encrypted=None
)
